FCL didn't include copy constructors for CollisionObject. Now that we're
sharing geometries across clones of ProximityEngine, the simplest way to
clone a CollisionObject is to simply copy construct one collision object from
another.

We were previously constructing a new CollisionObject from the components of
the original. This led to race conditions because the CollisionObject
constructors all performed write operations on the shared geometry. The copy
constructor promises not to do that, so it makes cloning collision objects
implicitly threadsafe.

This *could* be upstreamed, but the ambiguity around user data is such that it
may very will be a footgun. Drake's usage is safe because the user data isn't
truly a pointer -- merely an integer-encoded value.

--- include/fcl/narrowphase/collision_object-inl.h
+++ include/fcl/narrowphase/collision_object-inl.h
@@ -85,6 +85,10 @@ CollisionObject<S>::CollisionObject(
   computeAABB();
 }

+//==============================================================================
+template <typename S>
+CollisionObject<S>::CollisionObject(const CollisionObject& other) = default;
+
 //==============================================================================
 template <typename S>
 CollisionObject<S>::~CollisionObject()

--- include/fcl/narrowphase/collision_object.h
+++ include/fcl/narrowphase/collision_object.h
@@ -60,6 +60,21 @@ public:
                   const Matrix3<S>& R,
                   const Vector3<S>& T);

+  // Copy constructor.
+  //
+  // Note: the newly constructed copy will share the underlying geometry
+  // (safely via the shared_ptr). However, it will also share the user data
+  // pointer, which is a potential source for bugs. Whatever user data is being
+  // pointed to must outlive both the original as well as the copy collision
+  // objects. If the copy needs a separate user data object with its own
+  // lifespan, the caller is responsible for updating the user data after
+  // construction.
+  //
+  // Unlike the other constructors, this copy constructor does not perform any
+  // write operations on its geometry (i.e., triggering a local AABB
+  // computation).
+  CollisionObject(const CollisionObject& other);
+
   ~CollisionObject();

   /// @brief get the type of the object
